<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="s_PID_mod_proofs" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>PID-module structure theorems: proofs</title>
    <subsection xml:id="ss_uniqueness">
    <title>Proof of uniqueness</title>
    <p>
        We first examine the uniqueness claims in <xref ref="th_PID_mod_invar"/> and <xref ref="th_PID_mod_elem_div"/>. In proving this we will assume existence of decompositions of the given form.  
    </p>
    <p>
        Let's first see why the Betti number <m>n</m> is uniquely determined. If we have 
        <md>
            <mrow>M \amp \cong R^n \oplus \Tor M</mrow>
        </md>,
        then 
        <md>
            <mrow>\Tor M \amp \cong \Tor(R^n)\oplus \Tor (\Tor M)\cong \{0\}\oplus \Tor M</mrow>
        </md> 
        and thus
        <md>
            <mrow>M/\Tor(M) \amp \cong (R^n\oplus \Tor(M))/(\{0\}\oplus \Tor M)\cong R^n</mrow>
        </md>.
        Thus <m>n</m> is the rank of the free module <m>M/\Tor M</m>. Since the rank of a free module is well defined, we see that <m>n</m> is uniquely determined by the module <m>M</m>. More explicitly, we have 
        <md>
            <mrow>M \cong R^m\oplus \Tor M\amp \iff m=\rank M/\Tor M</mrow> 
        </md>.
    </p>
    <p>
        It remains to show that each of the two distinct decompositions of <m>\Tor M</m> described in <xref ref="th_PID_mod_invar"/> and <xref ref="th_PID_mod_elem_div"/> satisfy the specified uniqueness claims. First observe that the we can obtain the elementary divisor form from the invariant factor form using the Chinese remainder theorem: given <m>a=\prod_{i=1}^rp_i^{n_i}</m>, with <m>p_i</m> pairwise nonassociate irreducibles, the ideals <m>(p_i^{n_i})</m> are pairwise coprime, and thus 
    <md number="yes">
        <mrow>R/(a) \amp \cong \bigoplus_{i=1}^rR/(p_i^{n_i})</mrow>
    </md>.
Expanding out all the invariant factor quotients <m>R/(a_i)</m> in this way and then grouping all associate irreducible factors together, we obtain the elementary divisor form from the invariant factor form. Conversely, with a little bit of care you can group the elementary factor quotients together in such a way to get the invariant factor form. It is worth at least looking at one example of this reverse direction to see what the subtleties are. Consider the case <m>R=\Z</m> and the group 
<md>
    <mrow>A \amp \cong \Z/2\Z\oplus \Z/2^2\Z\oplus \Z/2^2\Z \oplus \Z/3\Z\oplus \Z/3\Z</mrow>
</md>.
We have 
<md>
    <mrow>A \amp \cong \Z/2\Z\oplus (\Z/2^2\Z\oplus \Z/3\Z)\oplus (\Z/2^2\Z\oplus \Z/3\Z) </mrow>
    <mrow> \amp \cong \Z/2\Z \oplus \Z/12\Z \oplus \Z/12\Z</mrow>
</md>.
It thus suffices to show that the uniqueness claim for the elementary divisor form holds. Since this decomposition is a decomposition of <m>\Tor M</m>, we will assume <m>M=\Tor M</m> is torsion. Suppose we have a decomposition
<md>
    <mrow>M \amp \cong \bigoplus_{i=1}^r \bigoplus_{j=1}^{m_j}R/(p_i^{n_{ij}}) </mrow>
</md>
where the <m>p_i</m> are pairwise nonassociate irreducible elements. In general, if <m>p</m> and <m>q</m> are nonassociate irreducible elements, then <m>p</m> and <m>q^n</m> are coprime for any positive integer <m>n</m>, from which it follows that multiplication by <m>p</m> is an automorphism of <m>R/(q^n)</m>. It follows that the <m>p</m>-primary component of <m>R/(q^n)</m> is <m>\{0\}</m> for any irreducible <m>q</m> not associate to <m>p</m> and positive integer <m>n</m>. Since <m>p</m>-primary components behave well with direct sums, we conclude that given the composition of <m>M</m> above, we have 
<md>
    <mrow>M(p_i^\infty) \amp \cong \bigoplus_{i=1}^{m_i}R/(p_i^{n_{ij}})</mrow>
</md>
for all <m>i</m>. In other words, not surprisingly, we extract <m>M(p_i^\infty)</m> from the decomposition above by taking just the direct summands that involve <m>p_i</m>.  Since <m>M(p_i^\infty)</m> is (up to isomorphism) uniquely determined by <m>M</m>, we have thus reduced the uniqueness problem to showing that each of these <m>p_i</m>-primary component decompositions is unique in the stipulated sense. From now on, we assume that <m>p</m> is an irreducible element, and that we have a module <m>M</m> with decomposition 
<md>
    <mrow>M \amp \cong \bigoplus_{i=1}^m R/(p^{n_i})</mrow>
</md>.
The uniqueness of the <m>n_i</m> appearing in such a decomposition is now given by the following result, which actually tells us how to compute the sequence <m>n_1\leq n_2\leq\dots \leq n_m</m>. 
</p>
<theorem xml:id="th_PID_mod_pprimary">
<title>PID-module <m>p</m>-primary components</title>
<statement>
<p>
Let <m>R</m> be a PID, let <m>p</m> be an irreducible element of <m>R</m>, and let <m>F_p=R/(p)</m>. Note that since <m>(p)</m> is a maximal ideal in <m>R</m>, <m>F_p</m> is a field. 
<ol>
    <li>
        <p>
            If <m>M</m> is a finitely generated <m>R</m>-module, then for all <m>k\geq 0</m>, <m>p^kM/p^{k+1}M</m> is a finite-dimensional <m>F_p</m>-vector space. In particular, <m>M/pM</m> is a <m>F_p</m>-vector space of finite dimension <m>\dim_{F_p}M/pM</m>.
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            Let <m>M=R/(p^n)</m> for some positive integer <m>n</m>. We have 
            <md>
        <mrow>p^kM/p^{k+1}M \amp \cong \begin{cases}
        F_p \amp \text{if } k&lt; n \\
        \{0\} \amp \text{if } k\geq n
        \end{cases}
    </mrow>
</md>
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            Suppose <m>M</m> is a finitely generated <m>R</m>-module satisfying 
            <md>
                <mrow>M \amp\cong  \bigoplus_{i=1}^m R/(p^{n_i})</mrow>
            </md>
    with <m>n_1\leq n_2\leq \dots\leq  n_m</m>. For each <m>k\geq 1</m>, define 
            <md>
                <mrow>m_k  \amp = \abs{\{j\in \{1,2,\dots, m\}\mid n_j=k\}}</mrow>
            </md>.
            We have 
            <md>
                <mrow>m_k \amp =\dim_{F_p}p^{k-1}M/p^{k}M-\dim_{F_p}p^{k}M/p^{k+1}M</mrow>
            </md>.
            It follows that the sequence <m>n_1\leq n_2\cdots \leq n_m</m> is uniquely determined by <m>M</m>. 
        </p>
    </li>
</ol>
</p>
</statement>
<proof>
<p>
</p>
</proof>
</theorem>

</subsection>
<subsection xml:id="ss_existence">
<title>Aligned bases</title>
<p>
    We now set about proving that the decompositions described in <xref ref="th_PID_mod_invar"/> exists for any finitely generated <m>R</m>-module, where <m>R</m> is a PID. Let <m>M=(m_1,m_2,\dots, m_n)</m> be a finitely generated <m>R</m>-module. From the surjective <m>R</m>-module homomorphism
    <md>
        <mrow>\phi\colon R^n \amp \rightarrow M</mrow>
        <mrow>(a_1,a_2,\dots, a_n) \amp \rightarrow \sum_{i=1}^n a_i m_i</mrow>
    </md>,
    we conclude from the first isomorphism theorem that <m>M\cong R^n/N</m>, where <m>N=\ker\phi</m>. We desire a nice computational technique for determining the quotient <m>R^n/N</m>: one that will hopefully give us the decomposition of <m>M</m> as in <xref ref="th_PID_mod_invar"/>. The next theorem provides exactly this. 
</p>



<theorem xml:id="th_pid_aligned_basis">
   <title>PID-module theorem: aligned bases</title>
   <statement>
   <p>
   Let <m>R</m> be a PID. Let <m>M</m> be free <m>R</m>-module of finite rank <m>m</m>, and let <m>N</m> be a nonzero submodule of <m>M</m>. 
   <ol>
    <li>
        <p>
            <m>N</m> is a free <m>R</m>-module and <m>\rank N\leq m</m>.
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            There is a basis <m>B=(m_i)_{i=1}^m</m> of <m>M</m> and nonzero elements <m>a_1,a_2,\dots, a_n\in R</m>, <m>n\leq m</m>, such that
            <md number="yes">
                <mrow>a_i \amp \mid a_{i+1}</mrow>
            </md>
            for all <m>1\leq i\leq n-1</m>, and 
            <md number="yes">
                <mrow>B' \amp =(a_im_i)_{i=1}^{n}</mrow>
            </md>           
            is a basis of <m>N</m>. 
        </p>
    </li>
   </ol>
   </p>
   </statement>
   <proof>
    <p>
        
    </p>
   </proof>
   </theorem>
   
   <definition xml:id="d_aligned_basis">
   <title>Aligned basis</title>
   <statement>
   <p>
   Let <m>R</m> be a commutative ring, let <m>M</m> be a free <m>R</m>-module, and let <m>N</m> be a free submodule of <m>M</m>. An <term>aligned basis</term> for <m>M</m> and <m>N</m> is a basis <m>B=(m_i)_{i\in I}</m> of <m>M</m> such that there is a subset <m>J\subseteq I</m> and tuple <m>(a_j)_{j\in J}</m> of elements in <m>R</m> such that <m>B'=(a_jm_j)_{j\in J}</m> is a basis of <m>N</m>.
   </p>
   </statement>
   </definition>
   
   <example xml:id="eg_gauss_ints_aligned_basis">
   <title>Aligned basis for <m>\Z[i]</m> as <m>\Z</m>-module</title>
   <statement>
   <p>
   Let <m>R=\Z[i]</m>, the ring of Gaussian integers, and let <m>\alpha=1+2i</m>. 
   <ol>
    <li>
        <p>
            Show that <m>M=\Z[i]</m>, considered as a <m>\Z</m>-module, is free of rank 2. 
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            Let <m>N</m> be the ideal of <m>\Z[i]</m> generated by <m>\alpha</m>: <ie/>, <m>N=\alpha\Z[i]</m>. Show that <m>N</m> is a free <m>\Z</m>-module of rank 2, and that <m>(1+2i, -2+i)</m> is a <m>\Z</m>-basis of <m>N</m>. 
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            Note that the standard <m>\Z</m>-basis <m>(1,i)</m> of <m>\Z[i]</m> is not an aligned basis of <m>M</m> and <m>N</m>. Show that <m>(1+2i,i)</m> is an aligned basis for <m>M</m> and <m>N</m>. 
        </p>
    </li>

   </ol>
   </p>
   </statement>
   <solution>
   <p>
   <ol>
    <li>
        <p>
            The tuple <m>(1,i)</m> is easily seen to be a <m>\Z</m>-basis of <m>\Z[i]</m>. Thus <m>\Z[i]\cong \Z^2</m>. 
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            The map <m>f_\alpha\colon \Z[i]\rightarrow \Z[i]</m> defined as <m>f_\alpha(\beta)=\beta\alpha</m> is an <m>\Z</m>-module homomorphism: 
            <md>
                <mrow>f_{\alpha}(m\beta+n\gamma)=(m\beta+n\gamma)\alpha=m\beta\alpha+n\beta\alpha=mf_{\alpha}(\beta)+nf_\alpha(\gamma)</mrow>
            </md>.
            The image is <m>\{\beta\alpha\mid \beta\in \Z[i]\}</m>, which is precisely the ideal generated by <m>\alpha</m> in <m>\Z[i]</m>. In other words, <m>\im f_\alpha=N</m>. The kernel of <m>f_\alpha</m> is trivial since <m>\Z[i]</m> is an integral domain! Thus  <m>f_\alpha</m> is an isomorphism of <m>\Z[i]</m> with <m>N</m>. It follows that <m>N\cong \Z^2</m>. In more detail, since <m>B=(1,i)</m> is a basis of <m>\Z[i]</m>, its image <m>f_\alpha(B)=(f_{\alpha}(1), f_{\alpha}(i))=(\alpha, i\alpha)=(1+2i, -2+i)
            </m> is a <m>\Z</m>-basis of <m>N</m>. 
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            Suppose by contradiction that <m>(1,i)</m> is an aligned basis of <m>\Z[i]</m> with respect to <m>N</m>. This would mean that there are integers <m>a,b\in \Z</m> with <m>a\mid b</m> such that <m>(a,bi)</m> is a generating set of <m>N</m>. However, <m>N</m> is the ideal generated by <m>1+2i</m>, which an irreducible element of <m>\Z[i]</m> lying over <m>5</m>. It follows that <m>N\cap \Z=(5)</m>. Since <m>a\in N\cap \Z</m>, we must have <m>5\mid a</m> and <m>5\mid b</m>. But then <m>5\mid m+ni</m> for all elements of <m>(a,bi)</m>: a contradiction, since <m>5\nmid 1+2i</m>. 
        </p>
        <p>
            The tuple <m>B'=(1+2i, i)</m> is easily seen to be linearly independent. Since 
            <md>
                <mrow>1 \amp =1(1+2i)+(-2)i</mrow>
                <mrow>i \amp =0(1+2i)+1i</mrow>
            </md>,
            it follows that <m>B'</m> is a spanning set of <m>\Z[i]</m> as a <m>\Z</m>-module. Lastly, we show that <m>B''=(1+2i, 5i)</m> is a basis of <m>N</m>. Since it is obtained from <m>B'</m> simply by scaling each basis element by a nonzero scalar, it is clearly linearly independent. Since 
            <md>
                <mrow>1+2i \amp =1(1+2i)+0\cdot 5i</mrow>
                <mrow>-2+i \amp =-2(1+2i)+1\cdot 5i</mrow>
            </md>
            and since <m>N=(1+2i, -2+i)</m>, it follows that <m>B''</m> is a spanning set of <m>N</m>. 
        </p>
    </li>
   </ol>
   </p>
   </solution>
   </example>
   <figure xml:id="fig_lattice_bases_pics">
